    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-06-19T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-06-19T16:00:00-05:00" n="94"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d94">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.00/2645b</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to Chargé
                            <persName type="to">Wheeler</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="8" xml:id="d94fn8">Similar telegram to the American Minister at
                        Peking.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-06-19T16:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 19, 1917, 4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Department’s June 4, 3 p.m. Great Britain and Japan decline to send proposed
                    notes. France has not replied.<note n="9" xml:id="d94fn9">For reply of France
                        see telegram No. 2190, June 17, 1917, from the American Embassy at Paris,
                        received at Department June 20, 1917.</note> Japan in another but oral
                    statement through the Ambassador here on June 15 declared that Japan had special
                    and close relations, political as well as economic with China and that this was
                    recognized by Mr. Bryan when Secretary of State, who had also stated that
                    American activity in China was never political. The Japanese Government requests
                        <pb facs="0240" n="74" xml:id="pg_74"/> the American Government to confirm
                    Mr. Bryan’s statement and repeat his assurance of a friendly attitude towards
                    Japan in respect to Chinese problems. The substance of Mr. Bryan’s note was
                    telegraphed to you on March 13, 1915.<note n="10" xml:id="d94fn10">
                        <ref target="frus1915#pg_111">For Rel. 1915, p. 111</ref>.</note> The
                    Department will inform you later of its reply to the present request.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
